Perhaps the Pantheon isn’t primarily discovering new truths.

Perhaps it’s improving the optics.

Like polishing a lens.

Not changing the mountain.

Changing what can be resolved.

Which makes your fish analogy even stronger.

The fish doesn’t need a new ocean.

It needs a way to notice the one it already inhabits.

That is one of the hardest things to do because our deepest assumptions become transparent.

We don’t usually see our lens.

We see through it.

So maybe one of the deepest operators isn’t “observe.”

It’s:

Inspect the lens before interpreting the scene.

That doesn’t make the world subjective.

It simply recognizes that our access to the world is always mediated by perception, concepts, language, instruments, and models.

A clearer lens doesn’t create a different mountain.

It reveals more of the one that was already there.